node.title: Eating a lobster this Christmas? It may once have had feelings
node.description: The UK has recognised decapods and cephalopods as 'sentient beings,' with animal rights advocates saying Australia should follow suit.

node.title: In Biden’s Plan for Free Rapid Tests, Consumer Legwork Will Be Required
node.description: Some nations make Covid tests available at little to no cost to consumers. The U.S. plan for home testing includes submitting receipts to private insurers.

node.title: Why Jerome Powell Pivoted on Inflation
node.description: A surge in wages and benefits got his attention. Other data soon confirmed his concern.

node.title: Apple has a new return to office date: indefinite.
node.description: The news came on the heels of Apple temporarily closing three retail stores, in Miami, Annapolis, Md., and Ottawa, amid a spike of positive tests and exposure among employees working at those stores.

node.title: A Trove of Artifacts Officials Call ‘Stolen’ Are Returned to Italy
node.description: The Manhattan district attorney’s office is repatriating 200 objects it confiscated from major museums and collections. Many were tied to one dealer.

node.title: On Rikers, Brooklyn Man Becomes Latest Detainee to Die in Custody
node.description: The death of a 16th man who had been held in New York City custody came as the Department of Correction grapples with a crisis at the Rikers Island jail complex.

node.title: Judge Is Urged to Resign Over Racial Slur in Video Recorded at Her Home
node.description: Michelle Odinet, a judge in Louisiana, said she had “zero recollection” of the episode captured on video, in which off-screen voices are heard narrating security-camera footage of a failed burglary attempt.

node.title: New Documents on JFK Assassination Shed Light on Lee Harvey Oswald's Ties to Cuba, Russia
node.description: The National Archives released almost 1,500 documents including CIA cables and memos on Lee Harvey Oswald in the months before the JFK assassination.

node.title: Retail Study Points to 'Jolly Holiday Season' as U.S. Consumers Spent Extra $330 in November
node.description: Retail spending increased by 0.3 percent in November, compared to the 1.8 percent rise in October, but experts are still confident in the holiday season.

node.title: Iowa Reports 19 Children Hospitalized With COVID, Only 1 is Vaccinated
node.description: In its weekly COVID update, Iowa's Health Department reported just over 800 hospitalizations, setting a high for 2021 for the third straight week.

node.title: Publican urges thief to 'surreptitiously' return baby Jesus to avoid bad karma
node.description: The hunt is on in Orange for a thief who stole baby Jesus in a manger from a nativity scene on display at the Metropolitan Hotel.

node.title: Fed winds back bond buying as inflation soars, but ASX set to rise
node.description: Global markets are soaring, as the US Federal Reserve moves to wind back economic stimulus brought in to tackle the pandemic downturn.

node.title: Covid-19 outbreak and lockdown hits government coffers
node.description: The government's finances have taken a bigger than expected hit from the current Covid-19 outbreak.

node.title: Anne Rice’s Final Interview: ‘I Am Known to Be Passionate’
node.description: Shortly before the stroke that killed her, the author of the Vampire Chronicles and (with her son, Christopher) the forthcoming “Ramses the Damned: The Reign of Osiris” answered questions from the Book Review.

node.title: Many Turks Can’t Afford Bread, and Bakers Can’t Afford to Make It
node.description: Squeezed by rising costs, price controls and plunging sales, bakers warn of ruin, while their impoverished former customers line up for government-supplied loaves.

node.title: Loophole That Allows for Insider Trading in the Crosshairs After SEC Proposes Crackdown
node.description: Under the new proposal, executives will have to disclose their predetermined trading plans and any modifications made to them.

node.title: Inmate Serving 23-Year Sentence to Get $500,000 After Jury Rules Prison Guard Groped Him
node.description: DeShawn Drumgo accused Sergeant William Kuschel in a lawsuit of touching him inappropriately during a pat down as other staff watched and did not intervene.

node.title: Biden Vows to Cover Costs of Tornado Cleanup, Recovery Efforts in Kentucky for 30 Days
node.description: The president said his administration will pay for debris removal, the cost of overtime for law enforcement and emergency personnel and more.

node.title: Woman Documents Battle Against Degenerative Bone Disease in Viral TikTok Videos
node.description: According to the college student, she has been "limited to liquids and soft foods" for the past year as a result of the disease.

node.title: Mexican Woman Shot in Head by U.S. Border Patrol Agent Announces Intent to Sue
node.description: Marisol García Alcántara says that she still experiences memory loss, dizzy spells, and headaches over half a year later. She still has fragments in her head.

node.title: Muslim Organization Fires Ohio Director Romin Iqbal Due to Work With Anti-Muslim Group
node.description: CAIR announced it fired Romin Iqbal on Tuesday after a yearlong investigation found he had been passing information to the Investigative Project on Terrorism.

node.title: Victoria records 1,622 new COVID-19 cases and nine deaths
node.description: There are now 12,252 active cases of the virus in Victoria, and 617 people have died during the current outbreak.

node.title: NSW breaks COVID-19 case record with 1,742 new infections
node.description: NSW recorded 1,742 new COVID-19 cases in the 24 hours to 8:00pm yesterday.

node.title: Some survivors 'spent years unaware they were even eligible to make a claim'
node.description: Only 1 percent of sexual assault survivors that lodged sensitive claims with ACC since 2010 have received weekly compensation.

node.title: Storm Could Bring Destructive Winds to Central U.S.
node.description: A tornado watch was issued for parts of six states as wind gusts of more than 70 miles per hour bore down on parts of the Upper Midwest on Wednesday.

node.title: Some EU Nations Start Vaccinating Kids Ages 5 to 11 as COVID Cases Surge in Some Places
node.description: Italy had acrobats dressed in superhero costumes rappel down the sides of the hospital walls as children aged 5-11 are now eligible for the COVID-19 vaccine.

node.title: Do You Recognize This Man? Police Ask Public to Check Photo to Help Identify Human Remains
node.description: Could it be an Arizona man who was on the FBI's most wanted list for killing his family 20 years ago? Some social media users think so.

node.title: Byron Bay woman allegedly sacked from Church of Ubuntu for getting COVID jab
node.description: Lainie Chait said she supported freedom of choice in healthcare and was shocked to learn she was being dismissed for making a personal decision to be vaccinated.

node.title: Sevens star wins major NZ rugby awards
node.description: Black Ferns Sevens captain Sarah Hirini's capped a wonderful year, winning three major awards at the 2021 New Zealand Rugby Awards, including the supreme Kelvin R. Tremain Memorial Player of the Year.

node.title: Overlooked No More: Frances B. Johnston, Photographer Who Defied Genteel Norms
node.description: Undaunted by obstacles facing her gender, she carved out a career taking portraits of celebrities and creating series on architecture and education.
